{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16765"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16765"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.22,0.12,0.1,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107367"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4090"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107367"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasingly heavy menstrual bleeding and pelvic pressure. She soaks through a pad every hour during her period and passes large clots. She reports urinary frequency and occasional difficulty emptying her bowels. She has no significant medical history but takes oral iron supplements. She has completed her family and does not want more children, but is reluctant to consider hysterectomy or major surgical interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with a palpable mass extending to the umbilicus. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 95 g/L (115-160), mean cell volume 75 fL (80-100), ferritin 8 \u00b5g/L (20-200). Transvaginal ultrasound shows multiple uterine fibroids, the largest measuring 20 cm. Magnetic resonance imaging confirms multiple intramural fibroids with a uterine volume of 750 mL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uterine artery embolisation","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone analogues","Endometrial ablation","Tranexamic acid","Myomectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic uterine fibroids causing both heavy menstrual bleeding and pressure symptoms. The large fibroid burden (uterine volume \u0026gt;750 mL) and the patient\u0027s desire to avoid hysterectomy make this a challenging management scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine artery embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option as it can effectively treat both the bleeding and pressure symptoms by reducing fibroid size. It is minimally invasive, has a shorter recovery time than surgery, and preserves the uterus. Success rates are around 85% for symptom improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E may reduce menstrual blood loss but would not address the underlying fibroid burden or pressure symptoms. It is more appropriate for smaller fibroids or when bleeding is the only symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyomectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be technically challenging given the multiple large fibroids and carries significant surgical risks. It is more appropriate for women who wish to preserve fertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to be technically challenging with multiple fibroids of this size and would not address the pressure symptoms. It is more suitable for heavy menstrual bleeding without significant uterine enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone analogues\u003C/strong\u003E could temporarily reduce fibroid size and bleeding but would cause menopausal symptoms and are not a long-term solution. They are mainly used pre-operatively to reduce fibroid size.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uterine artery embolisation is an effective alternative to hysterectomy for women with symptomatic fibroids who wish to avoid major surgery.","Large fibroids can cause both heavy menstrual bleeding and pressure symptoms.","Iron deficiency anaemia is a common complication of heavy menstrual bleeding that requires active management."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Uterine Artery Embolisation for the Treatment of Uterine Fibroids [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Uterine-artery-embolisation-for-the-treatment-of-uterine-fibroids.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16765"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T10:45:30+09:3